            <p>The manuscript by S. Spathariotis 
                <italic>et al.</italic> addresses a fundamental aspect, although rarely covered, of the green economy, namely the imperative need of recycling PGM (Pt, Ir, Pd, Ru&#x2026;) from the devices used for the production and use of green hydrogen. In particular the authors focus on the recovery of Pt from fuel cells, especially the fuel cells used in the automotive sector, and the Pt, Ir and Ru used in electrolyzers. The importance of this feature cannot be overestimated, since mining of PGM alone will not suffice to satisfy EU&#x2019;s expected demand of these metals. In addition, as properly identified by the authors, the largest reserves of PGMs, and some of the main companies controlling PMG markets are located in third countries.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> In their work, the authors present a technoeconomic analysis of the recovery and recycling of PGM metals making a case study for the hydrometallurgical, which according to the authors is superior to the pyrometallurgical one. A brief description of each process should be necessary in order to understand the key aspects of each process, emphasizing the advantages of the hydrometallurgical process. Do the authors know if this process is currently used at commercial level?</p>
            <p> Through the manuscript, some figures are given without citing references to support them. For instance, it is said that the sale price of the recovered materials could be 15% lower than current market prices. How do the authors get this figure? It is stated that between 30-60 g of Pt are used in fuel cell vehicles. This figure may be a little lower, between 10-20 g (see Thompson 
                <italic>et al.</italic> (2019
                <sup>
                    <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="rep-ref-29789-1">1</xref>
                </sup>), or SAE Int. J. Sust. Trans., Energy, Env., &amp; Policy / Volume 3, Issue 1, 2022).</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> In their case study, the authors aim to recover Pt, Pd, Ru and Ir from MEAs. What kind of MEAs use Pd?</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> It appears that three persons will be hired to process ca. 6.5 million MEAs in 5 years. This is more than 1200 MEAs per day. Is this figure correct?</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> In the list of equipment an automatic electrocatalyst sputtering is found? Is this equipment needed for preparing the electrocatalysts or for preparing MEAs?</p>
            <p>If applicable, is the statistical analysis and its interpretation appropriate?</p>
            <p>I cannot comment. A qualified statistician is required.</p>
